    "content": "Somalia's Prime Minister Hamza Abdi Barre has unveiled an extensive reform plan targeting Islamic education, religious institutions, and the modernization of public trust management. The announcement was made during a graduation ceremony for the first Master's cohort at the Faculty of Da'wa and Judiciary at the Somali National University.\n\nThis initiative marks the first time in Somalia's history that a national system for Islamic education has been established. The reforms include the restructuring of Quranic schools, which have traditionally operated without standardized oversight. The plan also seeks to invigorate religious bodies and enhance their role in society.\n\nThe move comes amid broader efforts by the federal government to strengthen governance and institutional capacity. By introducing a unified framework, authorities aim to ensure quality control and consistency in religious education, which plays a significant role in Somali communities.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, this development is particularly relevant as many families abroad seek clarity on the standards and accreditation of Islamic schools back home. The reforms could also influence how religious education is perceived and integrated into the diaspora's cultural preservation efforts.\n\nWhile details on implementation timelines and funding are still emerging, the initiative signals a shift toward greater regulation and modernization of a sector that has long operated informally. Observers will be watching for how these changes affect access, quality, and the balance between religious and secular education.\n\nRead the original report from Goobjoog here: https://goobjoog.com/2026/07/22/soomaaliya-oo-shaacisay-dib-u-habayn-ballaaran-oo-lagu-samaynayo-waxbarashada-islaamiga-ah/",
